snippet.textDisplay: Those HiAce vans that you saw at the end of your drive seem to be getting very popular recently. I'm in the SF bay area and for the past 6 months I have been seeing those late 80's early 90's right hand drive japanese vans like the HiAce, Delica, HiJet, Urvan driving on the road about once every other week. Seems like most are turned into campers, and are often times the 4 wheel drive models that have better ground clearance than something like a Westfalia. I know in other parts of the world they're very common and parts are readily available, but I would imagine having to import items every time you need to fix something would be kind of a pain.

snippet.textDisplay: Just a thought.... your still going to a Hyundai dealership for service. I would be thinking "where's the espresso machine?"  Hyundai is here to stay and "Genesis" is to what Lexus is to Toyota, Infinity is to Nissan,  and Acura is to Honda. The competitors in this class are Mercedes S class, BMW 7 series, and Audi A8, all of which cost more than the G90 Ultimate, but when you show up to any of these brands dealerships your going to have an espresso machine, along with an expensive facility, high end clientele, top notch loaners, highly trained service technicians, etc. Good luck getting that at your Hyundai/Genesis dealership. It reminds me of Volkswagen's failed attempt when they released the Phaeton back in 2002-2003 (why buy a VW Phaeton when you can buy an Audi A8?).
